03973nam a22005655i 9780226043449DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20092009ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802260434497 a10.7208/97802260434492doi  a(DE-B1597)524409  a(OCoLC)812510401  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aBF175.5.S48bB47 2010eb 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a155.32221 aBersani, Leo, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aIs the Rectum a Grave? :band Other Essays /cLeo Bersani. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2009] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (224 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tPART 1. The Sexual Subject -- t1. Is the Rectum a Grave? -- t2. Is There a Gay Art? -- t3. Gay Betrayals -- t4. Sociability and Cruising -- t5. Aggression, Gay Shame, and Almodóvar’s Art -- tPART 2. Toward an Aesthetic Subject -- t6. Against Monogamy -- t7. Sociality and Sexuality -- t8. Can Sex Make Us Happy? -- t9. Fr-oucault and the End of Sex -- t10. Psychoanalysis and the Aesthetic Subject -- t11. The Will to Know -- tPART 3. Two Interviews -- t12. A Conversation with Leo Bersani -- t13. Beyond Redemption: An Interview with Leo Bersani -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOver the course of a distinguished career, critic Leo Bersani has tackled a range of issues in his writing, and this collection gathers together some of his finest work. Beginning with one of the foundations of queer theory—his famous meditation on how sex leads to a shattering of the self, “Is the Rectum a Grave?”—this volume charts the inspired connections Bersani has made between sexuality, psychoanalysis, and aesthetics. Over the course of these essays, Bersani grapples with thinkers ranging from Plato to Descartes to Georg Simmel. Foucault and Freud recur as key figures, and although Foucault rejected psychoanalysis, Bersani contends that by considering his ideas alongside Freud’s, one gains a clearer understanding of human identity and how we relate to one another. For Bersani, art represents a crucial guide for conceiving new ways of connecting to the world, and so, in many of these essays, he stresses the importance of aesthetics, analyzing works by Genet, Caravaggio, Proust, Almodóvar, and Godard. Documenting over two decades in the life of one of the best minds working in the humanities today, Is the Rectum a Grave? and Other Essays is a unique opportunity to explore the fruitful career of a formidable intellect.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aAesthetics. 0aCruising (Sexual behavior). 0aGender identity. 0aPsychoanalysis and art. 0aPsychoanalysis. 0aQueer theory. 0aSex (Psychology). 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226043449423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226043449.jpg  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles